04318nam a22005055i 9780674245334DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20202020mau    fo  d z      eng d  a97806742453347 a10.4159/97806742453342doi  a(DE-B1597)549788  a(OCoLC)1144719790  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 4aKF5050 7aPOL0400102bisacsh04a342.73/0622231 aPrakash, Saikrishna Bangalore, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Living Presidency :bAn Originalist Argument against Its Ever-Expanding Powers /cSaikrishna Bangalore Prakash. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (336 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- t1. Kingly Beginnings -- t2. Why Presidents Amend the Constitution -- t3. How Presidents Amend the Constitution -- t4. The Living Presidency in a Living Constitution -- t5. From Constitutional Defender to Constitutional Amender -- t6. From First General to Declarer of Wars -- t7. From Chief Diplomat to Sole Master of Foreign Affairs -- t8. From Dutiful Servant of the Laws to Secondary Lawmaker -- t9. How to Recage the Executive Lion -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tAcknowledgments -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA constitutional originalist sounds the alarm over the presidency’s ever-expanding powers, ascribing them unexpectedly to the liberal embrace of a living Constitution. Liberal scholars and politicians routinely denounce the imperial presidency—a self-aggrandizing executive that has progressively sidelined Congress. Yet the same people invariably extol the virtues of a living Constitution, whose meaning adapts with the times. Saikrishna Bangalore Prakash argues that these stances are fundamentally incompatible. A constitution prone to informal amendment systematically favors the executive and ensures that there are no enduring constraints on executive power. In this careful study, Prakash contends that an originalist interpretation of the Constitution can rein in the “living presidency” legitimated by the living Constitution. No one who reads the Constitution would conclude that presidents may declare war, legislate by fiat, and make treaties without the Senate. Yet presidents do all these things. They get away with it, Prakash argues, because Congress, the courts, and the public routinely excuse these violations. With the passage of time, these transgressions are treated as informal constitutional amendments. The result is an executive increasingly liberated from the Constitution. The solution is originalism. Though often associated with conservative goals, originalism in Prakash’s argument should appeal to Republicans and Democrats alike, as almost all Americans decry the presidency’s stunning expansion. The Living Presidency proposes a baker’s dozen of reforms, all of which could be enacted if only Congress asserted its lawful authority.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aExecutive powerzUnited States. 0aPresidentsxLegal status, laws, etc.zUnited States. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / American Government / Executive Branch.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHarvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311069005740uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/978067424533440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674245334423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780674245334.jpg  a978-3-11-069005-7  Harvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles